The Herald Lynn Munjanja Herald Correspondent Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe Governor John Mangudya held a press conference today where he officially announced that the Gold coin is now in the market. About two thousand coins have been disbursed to all banks. The initial price for each coin is US$1 823.8 or $805 745.35. <img class="size-full wp-image-631370 aligncenter" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/07/WhatsApp-Image-2022-07-25-at-1.05.18-PM.jpeg" alt="" width="1280" height="788" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/07/WhatsApp-Image-2022-07-25-at-1.05.18-PM.jpeg 1280w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/07/WhatsApp-Image-2022-07-25-at-1.05.18-PM-360x222.jpeg 360w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/07/WhatsApp-Image-2022-07-25-at-1.05.18-PM-768x473.jpeg 768w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/07/WhatsApp-Image-2022-07-25-at-1.05.18-PM-680x419.jpeg 680w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> Gold coins can also be purchased in denominated currencies such as the South African Rand, Botswana Pula, Austrian Dollar, British Pound and Euro.